WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:06.000
Let's start. I'm a mother of two, so I have to start with a story, right?

00:00:06.000 --> 00:00:13.000
Whenever I'm away for a while, I do miss my kids, and I look forward to seeing them again.

00:00:13.000 --> 00:00:20.000
But then, coming back home, opening the door, I'm met with excitement.

00:00:20.000 --> 00:00:31.000
Stomping feet, you know, hands reaching, grabbing, the voices louder and louder and louder until the point of squeaking.

00:00:31.000 --> 00:00:36.000
It's fair to say I get a bit overwhelmed by the attention.

00:00:36.000 --> 00:00:44.000
And somewhat similar feelings can be triggered when maintaining an open source project, especially if it's a big one.

00:00:44.000 --> 00:00:48.000
In our case, that's Apache Arrow.

00:00:48.000 --> 00:00:57.000
So, to give a bit more context then, Alenka and I met when we were both working as apprentices on the Apache Arrow project, learning how to be open source maintainers.

00:00:57.000 --> 00:01:00.000
And it was like a really exciting time.

00:01:00.000 --> 00:01:08.000
Apache Arrow is a bit of a unique open source project in that because there are so many different implementations of Arrow in different languages,

00:01:08.000 --> 00:01:17.000
you've got a huge number of people all collaborating together on one repository and kind of the multiple ones there and the wider Arrow ecosystem.

00:01:17.000 --> 00:01:20.000
So, this can be really advantageous in a lot of ways.

00:01:20.000 --> 00:01:24.000
There's just so much collaboration happens that, like, wouldn't have otherwise.

00:01:24.000 --> 00:01:30.000
But actually, there can be some challenges associated with that.

00:01:30.000 --> 00:01:33.000
Let's look at the GitHub issue tracker of Apache Arrow.

00:01:33.000 --> 00:01:36.000
This is the picture you see when you arrive there.

00:01:36.000 --> 00:01:38.000
It's quite a big number of issues.

00:01:38.000 --> 00:01:39.000
Agree?

00:01:39.000 --> 00:01:40.000
Yeah.

00:01:40.000 --> 00:01:42.000
Over 4,000 still open.

00:01:42.000 --> 00:01:44.000
Yeah, sorry.

00:01:44.000 --> 00:01:48.000
Over 20,000 were already closed.

00:01:48.000 --> 00:02:01.000
But if we zoom in on just the last year, and only R and Python because it is a part where we work on, there were over 500 pull requests submitted, over 1,000 issues open.

00:02:01.000 --> 00:02:12.000
And the interesting thing is that almost half of those issues were opened by new contributors, meaning each issue was opened by a different person.

00:02:12.000 --> 00:02:16.000
And for every person, that was the first issue they opened on the repo.

00:02:16.000 --> 00:02:17.000
Right?

00:02:17.000 --> 00:02:20.000
So, this is quite exciting.

00:02:20.000 --> 00:02:22.000
So, what's the problems this can cause?

00:02:22.000 --> 00:02:27.000
So, we're tracking information from GitHub issues and pull requests.

00:02:27.000 --> 00:02:29.000
We've got questions on Stack Overflow.

00:02:29.000 --> 00:02:31.000
And we've also got the mailing list.

00:02:31.000 --> 00:02:34.000
And this is a huge amount of information to manage.

00:02:34.000 --> 00:02:51.000
And in terms of thinking about the work done on an open source project, the important work in terms of the code base is responding to issues, fixing bugs, adding features, doing releases, but not really managing the project itself.

00:02:51.000 --> 00:02:57.000
What we want is to be able to quickly get to the right information so we can get on with the fun stuff.

00:02:58.000 --> 00:03:04.000
And as well as that, it can be really tricky just to get an idea of, like, what's going on and seeing what's changing over time.

00:03:04.000 --> 00:03:10.000
So, for example, let's say we had an increase of issues open since the last release.

00:03:10.000 --> 00:03:14.000
That might indicate bugs that we're not aware of that we want to get fixed.

00:03:14.000 --> 00:03:16.000
But also contributors.

00:03:16.000 --> 00:03:21.000
So, contributors are the lifeblood of any open source project.

00:03:21.000 --> 00:03:32.000
But if you're new to a project, let's say you open up an issue or maybe even a pull request, and nobody gets back to you for weeks or even months, you're going to be discouraged.

00:03:32.000 --> 00:03:35.000
And you might not want to continue to stay involved.

00:03:35.000 --> 00:03:42.000
So, what we really want is to be able to get to these new contributors as quickly as possible and really just get that collaboration going.

00:03:44.000 --> 00:03:46.000
And kind of reduce some of that.

00:03:47.000 --> 00:03:58.000
Well, actually, when I think about the problems that we're talking about here, these aren't problems that are unique to Arrow or unique to open source projects or even just kind of unique to us.

00:03:58.000 --> 00:04:05.000
Like, everybody's got things to think about in terms of how do we foster collaboration between different people with different things going on?

00:04:05.000 --> 00:04:08.000
And how do we reduce information overload?

00:04:08.000 --> 00:04:15.000
So, what we're going to talk to you about today is a dashboard that we created to manage all of this information.

00:04:15.000 --> 00:04:18.000
But actually, this isn't just about the dashboard.

00:04:18.000 --> 00:04:22.000
It is about building the dashboard and the technology choices we made there.

00:04:23.000 --> 00:04:30.000
But it's also about building diverse collaborations that allow everybody to contribute in their own way.

00:04:30.000 --> 00:04:35.000
And building curiosity for the ideas and technology that enable all of this.

00:04:37.000 --> 00:04:40.000
So, let's first take a look at the dashboard itself.

00:04:41.000 --> 00:04:44.000
We mentioned a sheer number of issues and pull requests created.

00:04:44.000 --> 00:04:52.000
So, what we wanted to do first is to kind of split the information so we can get to the right one quickly.

00:04:52.000 --> 00:04:55.000
So, we did two pages. One for Python, the other for R.

00:04:56.000 --> 00:04:59.000
Both of the pages have the same structure, though.

00:05:02.000 --> 00:05:06.000
We also wanted to have an understanding of what's going on at a higher level.

00:05:06.000 --> 00:05:09.000
So, the first thing we see here is the Summary tab.

00:05:10.000 --> 00:05:18.000
In the Summary tab, we can see, for example, issues that have been created lately or PRs and similar information.

00:05:20.000 --> 00:05:24.000
We wanted to prioritize new contributors, as mentioned.

00:05:25.000 --> 00:05:32.000
So, in the individual tabs for issues and PRs, you can see the list of those and the highlight. See?

00:05:33.000 --> 00:05:41.000
So, this, what's highlighted, is the issues or PRs opened by a new contributor, so we can identify them easily and get to that first.

00:05:45.000 --> 00:05:48.000
The next, yes, it's the Stack Overflow tab.

00:05:48.000 --> 00:05:53.000
Here you can find questions asked on Stack Overflow connected to Python on R.

00:05:54.000 --> 00:06:00.000
Again, we highlighted information that's important to us, which is, is this answer accepted yet or not?

00:06:01.000 --> 00:06:04.000
So, if not, we can get to that first.

00:06:06.000 --> 00:06:08.000
The last, but not the least, Mailing List.

00:06:09.000 --> 00:06:18.000
I know it's a bit of an old-school thing, but a note we want to add here is that for any Apache Arrow, this is the most important communication channel.

00:06:19.000 --> 00:06:23.000
And if there's a topic that's important, it's discussed on the Mailing List.

00:06:24.000 --> 00:06:30.000
So, here you can find a list of emails that have been sent in the last month.

00:06:31.000 --> 00:06:35.000
So, this is the dashboard we made, and now we're going to talk about how we got them.

00:06:37.000 --> 00:06:41.000
So, in terms of how we made the dashboard, we decided to use Quarto dashboards.

00:06:42.000 --> 00:06:50.000
So, this is a feature of Quarto that's been available since January this year, and it allows you to create dashboards, but using Quarto kind of syntax.

00:06:51.000 --> 00:06:57.000
So, in terms of the different technologies we were trying to choose between before we decided on Quarto dashboards,

00:06:58.000 --> 00:07:04.000
we considered Shiny, creating it as a Quarto document, or the one that we went with in the end, a Quarto dashboard.

00:07:05.000 --> 00:07:09.000
So, here are the few kind of criteria that we had to make this decision.

00:07:10.000 --> 00:07:13.000
So, the first thing was that we wanted something with a dashboard aesthetic.

00:07:14.000 --> 00:07:16.000
We didn't want a document that we had to scroll through.

00:07:16.000 --> 00:07:21.000
We just wanted to be able to look at it, click on a couple of things, and get the information that we needed.

00:07:23.000 --> 00:07:29.000
The next thing that was important to us was the fact that with Quarto dashboards, you can work with markdown syntax.

00:07:30.000 --> 00:07:33.000
So, we were thinking about what is this project about?

00:07:34.000 --> 00:07:38.000
And really, the information in it, it doesn't really change that often.

00:07:39.000 --> 00:07:43.000
We were refreshing the data like once a day, and we didn't need a huge amount of interactivity.

00:07:44.000 --> 00:07:51.000
And Shiny is great, but it felt like just too much for this project, because the idea here was to reduce the maintenance burden.

00:07:52.000 --> 00:07:56.000
And so, being able to work with markdown syntax made life a lot easier for us.

00:07:58.000 --> 00:08:01.000
Another thing we had to consider was deployment of the dashboard.

00:08:02.000 --> 00:08:07.000
So, we decided we wanted to deploy it with GitHub Actions, mainly because that's something that I'm familiar with,

00:08:08.000 --> 00:08:10.000
and that was something we could get working quickly.

00:08:10.000 --> 00:08:14.000
And actually, you can deploy Shiny apps when it's Shiny live on GitHub Actions,

00:08:15.000 --> 00:08:18.000
but it still just felt simpler to go with the Quarto dashboard option.

00:08:20.000 --> 00:08:26.000
But actually, the most important thing for us was that we wanted to work in something where we could have both R and Python combined.

00:08:27.000 --> 00:08:35.000
We didn't want to divide the project up between, okay, this bit is yours, so you can do that in Python, and this bit is mine, so I'll do that in R.

00:08:36.000 --> 00:08:38.000
We wanted to be able to both work on all of the different bits.

00:08:38.000 --> 00:08:40.000
So, we could just have fun and enjoy it.

00:08:43.000 --> 00:08:48.000
So, just having a bit of a think about the technological decisions and choices we had to make,

00:08:49.000 --> 00:08:54.000
when combining R and Python in a Quarto dashboard, I think there's one decision that has to be made up front,

00:08:55.000 --> 00:08:57.000
and that's whether you start from R or you start from Python.

00:08:58.000 --> 00:09:05.000
So, starting from R, you're using the NitR engine and reticulate to pass data between R and Python.

00:09:05.000 --> 00:09:10.000
Starting from Python, it's using Jupyter as the engine and using RPy2.

00:09:12.000 --> 00:09:15.000
And we were thinking, okay, can we do a bit of a compare and contrast of these?

00:09:16.000 --> 00:09:19.000
But to be honest, when we were kind of building this, we found they're pretty similar approaches.

00:09:20.000 --> 00:09:27.000
In terms of the project, we went starting from R solely because I was saying that at the time, and it was what I was familiar with.

00:09:27.000 --> 00:09:30.000
So, thinking about kind of the structure of the dashboard and the code inside it,

00:09:31.000 --> 00:09:33.000
we started off having a mix of scripts.

00:09:34.000 --> 00:09:36.000
So, some were in R, some were in Python.

00:09:37.000 --> 00:09:41.000
And then we had this index Quarto markdown document that orchestrated all of that.

00:09:42.000 --> 00:09:44.000
So, that was in a mix of R and Python.

00:09:45.000 --> 00:09:47.000
But then we had this data Quarto markdown document,

00:09:48.000 --> 00:09:51.000
and that actually enabled us to use a really cool feature of Quarto.

00:09:51.000 --> 00:09:53.000
So, there's this concept of Quarto includes.

00:09:54.000 --> 00:09:58.000
So, includes allow you to reuse information or code across multiple documents,

00:09:59.000 --> 00:10:02.000
or in our case, multiple times in the same document.

00:10:03.000 --> 00:10:07.000
So, this code snippet you can see now is from that index QMD file.

00:10:08.000 --> 00:10:11.000
And we've got their high-level headings, pyro or R.

00:10:12.000 --> 00:10:15.000
We've got a variable, which is a string.

00:10:15.000 --> 00:10:18.000
And we've got their high-level headings, pyro or R.

00:10:19.000 --> 00:10:21.000
We've got a variable, lang.

00:10:22.000 --> 00:10:23.000
So, we set that to Python or R.

00:10:24.000 --> 00:10:28.000
And then we include the data Quarto markdown document, and that's it.

00:10:29.000 --> 00:10:31.000
And we get the same dashboard for the different languages.

00:10:32.000 --> 00:10:35.000
And the reason this was really important to us is that when we started this project,

00:10:36.000 --> 00:10:40.000
Alenka and I didn't want this to be a collaboration between us that only benefit the two of us.

00:10:40.000 --> 00:10:44.000
We wanted to be able to roll this out to other bits of the Arrow dev community.

00:10:45.000 --> 00:10:49.000
So, let's say the Arrow C++ developers would make good use of this dashboard.

00:10:50.000 --> 00:10:52.000
We could just roll this out, like, in about 30 seconds to them.

00:10:53.000 --> 00:10:55.000
So, that was super important to us.

00:10:56.000 --> 00:11:00.000
Okay. So, the last kind of technical question we wanted to ask is,

00:11:01.000 --> 00:11:03.000
like, how much R and how much Python do we end up in the end?

00:11:04.000 --> 00:11:09.000
So, quite conveniently, GitHub on a repository page actually has this information.

00:11:10.000 --> 00:11:14.000
So, we found we ended up actually with a pretty even split, which was pretty cool.

00:11:15.000 --> 00:11:19.000
So, yeah. So, that's all of the technological choices and the thinking around that.

00:11:20.000 --> 00:11:23.000
But actually, I don't think this is the most interesting thing about this project.

00:11:24.000 --> 00:11:27.000
I think it's actually much more interesting thinking about exactly how we got there.

00:11:28.000 --> 00:11:35.000
And the first thing we needed to do was build on curiosity for both of technology and ideas.

00:11:35.000 --> 00:11:41.000
We really needed to start with having honest discussions about our current approaches to maintenance.

00:11:42.000 --> 00:11:48.000
We realized we struggled with the same difficulties, but we did approach them from a different perspective.

00:11:49.000 --> 00:11:56.000
I, at the end, set up email filters for GitHub notifications and mainly used that.

00:11:57.000 --> 00:12:02.000
Nick had various scripts that handled all the different sources we had.

00:12:02.000 --> 00:12:10.000
We both felt overwhelmed by the amount of information and we realized we were missing things.

00:12:11.000 --> 00:12:12.000
Things that were important, right?

00:12:13.000 --> 00:12:15.000
For example, the new contributors.

00:12:16.000 --> 00:12:23.000
It's really important and we felt like we were both frustrated by the fact that we didn't get to them as fast as we wanted.

00:12:24.000 --> 00:12:26.000
Or maybe we didn't even get to them.

00:12:27.000 --> 00:12:29.000
So, this had to be a part of the solution.

00:12:30.000 --> 00:12:36.000
The sharing, getting an opinion from somebody else, a new perspective for us created new ideas.

00:12:37.000 --> 00:12:38.000
And the process became exciting.

00:12:39.000 --> 00:12:43.000
It was highly motivating to move towards a solution together.

00:12:44.000 --> 00:12:53.000
And the cool part at the end was that the solution became something that other contributors, other maintainers could also use.

00:12:54.000 --> 00:12:58.000
Which leads me to my next point of building diverse collaboration.

00:12:59.000 --> 00:13:05.000
We both feel it's really important that everyone is allowed to contribute in their own way.

00:13:06.000 --> 00:13:08.000
We have different skill sets.

00:13:09.000 --> 00:13:14.000
I like both R and Python, but the most comfortable I feel is in Python.

00:13:15.000 --> 00:13:20.000
Nick can also do both, but the most comfortable she feels is in R.

00:13:21.000 --> 00:13:23.000
Nick's head is bubbling with good ideas.

00:13:24.000 --> 00:13:26.000
I like to tidy up things, right?

00:13:26.000 --> 00:13:28.000
So, we have these different skill sets.

00:13:29.000 --> 00:13:42.000
And then, because together with the tools we chose for this process, it was much easier to work together in this process.

00:13:43.000 --> 00:13:49.000
So, we didn't have to, as Nick mentioned, we didn't have to climb different ladders to get to the solution.

00:13:50.000 --> 00:13:53.000
We used one and helped each other climb it.

00:13:53.000 --> 00:13:57.000
It was faster, nicer, and much more fun.

00:13:58.000 --> 00:14:10.000
If we start with Python and R script that Nick already had with dealing with the sources of information,

00:14:11.000 --> 00:14:19.000
I took them, leveled them up, connected them together in the dashboard, and we both worked on how to pass data between R and Python.

00:14:20.000 --> 00:14:25.000
Nick did the core dashboard and also GitHub Actions deployment.

00:14:26.000 --> 00:14:32.000
We both worked on the display content of the dashboard itself, some in R, some in Python.

00:14:33.000 --> 00:14:41.000
And what we needed to do here was iterate on the feedback and update to select the data we cared about most.

00:14:42.000 --> 00:14:49.000
So, Nick at the end said, this is cool, I learned Python environments and dependency management.

00:14:50.000 --> 00:14:53.000
I learned about portal, which ended up to be really simple to use.

00:14:54.000 --> 00:15:04.000
So, plus we both had to learn to select the data that will help us solve the problem, because this is not so clear.

00:15:05.000 --> 00:15:07.000
You have to iterate, you have to find and select.

00:15:08.000 --> 00:15:17.000
So, these different skill sets we have and the different background made us work and learn on things we wouldn't otherwise.

00:15:18.000 --> 00:15:21.000
And ultimately, we got much further than we would if we were working alone.

00:15:26.000 --> 00:15:30.000
We have a challenge for you that with that we'll end this talk.

00:15:31.000 --> 00:15:34.000
We would like to challenge you to, there's still some time today, it's not the end yet,

00:15:34.000 --> 00:15:40.000
to talk to somebody at the conference about a problem you're interested in or you're trying to solve.

00:15:41.000 --> 00:15:43.000
It doesn't have to be tech.

00:15:44.000 --> 00:15:46.000
Talk and see what happens.

00:15:47.000 --> 00:15:48.000
Thank you.

00:16:04.000 --> 00:16:05.000
Thank you.

